SIMPLE: flanker
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Flanker
<hw>Flank"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who, or that
which, flanks, as a skirmisher or a body of troops sent out upon the
flanks of an army to guard a line of march, or a fort projecting so as
to command the side of an assailing body.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They threw out <qex>flankers</qex>, and endeavored to dislodge
their assailants.</q> <rj><qau>W. Irwing.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flanker</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Flanker
<hw>Flank"er</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Flankered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Flankering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[See <er>Flank</er>, <pos>v.
t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To defend by lateral
fortifications.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir T.
Herbert.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To attack sideways.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Evelyn.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flannel</ent>⟦br⟧
